## Stopping the Nightmare

The `.then()` structure is messy. It creates a chain of nested callbacks.

In 2017, JavaScript released a true miracle called **`async / await`**. 

It allows developers to write Asynchronous background code using completely normal-looking Synchronous syntax! We don't have to write `.then()` anymore!

All we do is put the word `await` right before the `fetch` command. 

```javascript
// Instead of then(), we just force the code to Await the promise!
let response = await fetch('https://google.com/data');
let data = await response.json();

console.log(data);
```

## async functions

There is one iron-clad rule: **You can ONLY use the `await` keyword inside of a function officially labelled as `async`.**

You must explicitly warn JavaScript that a function contains a slowing-down `await` keyword, so it can throw the *entire function wrapper* into the background lane!

```javascript
// 1. Label the wrapper function 'async'
async function getWeather() {
  // 2. We can now use 'await' inside safely!
  let result = await fetch('https://api.weather.com');
  console.log("Done!");
}

// 3. The exact millisecond we execute this, it throws into the background
getWeather();
console.log("This log prints IMMEDIATELY before the weather is done! No freezing!");
```

